04135nmm a2200697Ia 9780814769928DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147699287 a10.18574/nyu/9780814769928.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)680872  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0010002bisacsh1 aAustin, Algernon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAchieving Blackness :bRace, Black Nationalism, and Afrocentrism in the Twentieth Century /cAlgernon Austin. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tPreface -- tContents -- t1 Making Races -- t2 Asiatic Identity in the Nation of Islam -- t3 Achieving Blackness during the Black Power Era -- t4 The Racial Structures of Black Power -- t5 The Racial Ideology of Afrocentrism -- t6 Conservative Black Nationalism in the Afrocentric Era -- t7 Change in Black Nationalism in the Twentieth Century -- t8 Making Races, Making Ethnicities -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAchieving Blackness offers an important examination of the complexities of race and ethnicity in the context of black nationalist movements in the United States. By examining the rise of the Nation of Islam, the Black Power Movement of the 1960s and 1970s, and the “Afrocentric era” of the 1980s through 1990s Austin shows how theories of race have shaped ideas about the meaning of “Blackness” within different time periods of the twentieth-century. Achieving Blackness provides both a fascinating history of Blackness and a theoretically challenging understanding of race and ethnicity. Austin traces how Blackness was defined by cultural ideas, social practices and shared identities as well as shaped in response to the social and historical conditions at different moments in American history. Analyzing black public opinion on black nationalism and its relationship with class, Austin challenges the commonly held assumption that black nationalism is a lower class phenomenon. In a refreshing and final move, he makes a compelling argument for rethinking contemporary theories of race away from the current fascination with physical difference, which he contends sweeps race back to its misconceived biological underpinnings. Achieving Blackness is a wonderful contribution to the sociology of race and African American Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  aAchieving.  aBlackness.  aStates.  aUnited.  ablack.  acomplexities.  acontext.  aethnicity.  aexamination.  aimportant.  amovements.  anationalist.  aoffers.  arace.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814769928.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814769928423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814769928/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles